speech.p:
I beg to move Amendment No. 543, in page 21, line 9, at end insert:
The Scottish Consolidated Fund shall have three sources of revenue—


(a) the proceeds of personal income tax levied upon Scottish residents as set out in Schedule (Income Tax in Scotland) and collected by the Inland Revenue. The Scottish Assembly may reduce the rates at which this income tax is levied;

(b) fifty per cent. of the proceeds of assigned excise taxes levied in Scotland. The assigned excise taxes are tobacco duty, alcohol duty, the duties on hydrocarbon oils and the duties on betting and gaming. The administration and collection of these taxes will continue to be the responsibility of the United Kingdom Customs and Excise and the Scottish Assembly will have no power to alter the rate of these taxes;

(c) an equalisation payment from the Treasury which will be authorised by the Chancellor of the Exchequer if the receipts of personal income tax and the half share of the assigned excise taxes are together more than 10 per cent. short of the Scottish proportion of public expenditure. In calculating whether a shortfall takes place, personal income tax will be assumed to be levied at the U.K. standard rate. The Scottish proportion of public expenditure will be that sum which stands in the same relation to each year's U.K. public expenditure as the sum spent on the total of devolved services stands in relation to U.K. public expendi-


ture in the year in which this Bill is enacted. If the sums raised by personal income tax (again calculated at the standard U.K. rate) and the half share of the assigned excise taxes are together greater than the Scottish proportion of public expenditure by ten per cent. or more of that sum, the surplus will be paid from the Scottish Consolidated Fund into the Treasury.".
